{
  "title": "Unit Testing Stream Processing in FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer provides a comprehensive guide on how to write tests for stream processing in FastAPI applications using Python 3.12+ and its new features.",
  "key_points": [
    "Embrace the power of async context managers for working with streams.",
    "Use test-time stubs or mocks for external services if necessary.",
    "Implement test cases that verify the expected behavior of your stream processing functions.",
    "Utilize FastAPI's built-in test client to simulate incoming requests and responses."
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "async def mock_stream():\n    async for _ in range(10):\n        yield 'mock data'\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef stream():\n    return mock_stream()"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "async def test_process_stream():\n    async with client(\'/process\') as res:\n        response = await res.request(\'POST\', data={'stream': stream()})\n        # Verify the response..."
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ introduces async context managers and improved type hints, which make it easier to write stream processing tests.",
    "FastAPI v0.74.0 or later is required for using the built-in test client."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "Be aware that testing streams can be more complex due to their asynchronous nature and potential buffering issues.",
    "It's important to handle edge cases, such as when the stream ends prematurely or exceptions occur during processing."
  ]
